035","about 1025":"about 1025","1087":"1087","1054":"1054","Ferrières-la-Verrerie, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Ferrières-la-Verrerie, Orne, Lower Normandy, France","Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","Orne, Basse-Normandie, West Kingdom of the Franks":"Orne, Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Adeline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["diminutive of <i>Adèle</i> (  see  Adele  ), used occasionally in England from the early 16th century onwards, and now also found in the wider English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Adeline de Beaumont was born about 1025, in Orne, Lower Normandy, France as the daughter of Richard De Beaumont and Isabell De Vermandois. She had at least 1 son with Guillaume II Talvas. She died in Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France."},"et":{"about 1025–":"umbes 1025–Surnud","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","0995–1054":"0995–1054","1035–1087":"1035–1087","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","0995":"0995","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","about 1025":"umbes 1025","1087":"1087","1054":"1054","Ferrières-la-Verrerie, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Ferrières-la-Verrerie, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Orne, Basse-Normandie, West Kingdom of the Franks":"Orne, Basse-Normandie, 